        <div class="msgSubject">The storylines behind Levequests are not very good. At all.</div>
        <div class="sm notbold">
          
          Posted: 2010-11-11 18:37:30 | Edited: Nov 12 2010 12:06am  | <input type="checkbox" name="quote-128952225032052413" id="quote-128952225032052413" class="msgQuoteCheck" onchange="multiQuote2()"/><label for="quote-128952225032052413" onclick="multiQuote2()"> Quote</label>  | <a href="/forum.html?forum=173&amp;mid=128952225032052413&amp;post=1&amp;replyto=128952225032052413&amp;page=1" class="icon-replytothis" rel="nofollow">Reply to Post</a> | <a id="FOLLOW_MID_128952225032052413" onclick="followToggle('add','128952225032052413')" href="javascript:" class="icon-follow">Follow</a> 
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="msgWhoFrame">
        <div class="msgUM"><a class="msgWhoName " href="/users/Rhianu">Rhianu</a></div><div class="msgAvatar"></div><div class="msgStar"><img src="http://common.zam.com/shared/s2.gif" alt="*"/><img src="http://common.zam.com/shared/s2.gif" alt="*"/></div><div class="msgWhoNum">297 posts</div>
        <div class="msgScore">
          Score: Decent  
          <div class="msgRatings"></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="msgContentFrame">For as long as anyone can remember, the FINAL FANTASY brandname has always carried with it the expectation of amazing stories, epic tales of valor, courage, and love; grand narratives woven with the expert fidelity of an old and wisened loremaster. And in the Main Scenario Quests, this expectation is fulfilled with all the pomp and flair we've come to expect from over twenty years of the dexterous craftsmanship received under the hands of those talented people working at Square-Enix. Yet, for some peculiar reason, Square-Enix has chosen not to extend that same talent to the Levequest aspect of this game. Some games have good stories. Many games have bad stories. FINAL FANTASY XIV is one of the few titles I have ever seen where good stories and bad stories have been mixed together in the <i>same game</i>. Clearly Square-Enix knows how to tell a good story, so the question is, why don't they? Why don't they write stories for the Levequests that are just as good as the stories seen in the Main Scenario Quests? I know the Levequests are not supposed to be the central aspect of the game's plot, but they could at least be entertaining. <br /> <br />I've witnessed many FFXIV players discussing the storylines behind Levequests, and something I've noticed is that many of them seem to be under the impression that Levequests have storylines just as good as the storylines you'd see in regular quests in any other MMORPG. Unfortunately, this is simply not the case. I don't know if those FFXIV players who claim such things have never touched another MMO, or if they're just delusional, but the fact remains that the story-text for Levequests is sub-par compared to other games in the genre. Now I feel I should warn you that in a little bit I'm going to be making a comparison to World of Warcraft, so if that bothers you, then you should probably just stop reading right now and leave this topic. The suggestion board is no place for those who would let their personal bias get in the way of seeing the good that other games have to offer. <br /> <br />Now as I was saying, after listening to many people (both those who hate the game as well as those who love it) talk about the Levequests, I noticed that many of those who love the game do not understand how Levequests are different from regular quests in other MMOs. <br /> <br />In FFXIV you talk to a single NPC standing behind a counter to get a Levequest, then go to the location that the Levequest describes, kill the targets at that location, and touch the Aetherial Node that appears for a reward. Then you go back to that same NPC again and get another quest. <br /> <br />But in other MMORPGS (including WoW and SE's first MMORPG, FFXI) you obtained quests by talking to many different NPC scattered all around town, then from there went out to the location described in the quest, killed the targets at that location, and returned to the NPC who gave you the quest for a reward. That NPC might have another quest for you, or he might not. But if not, there were bound to be other NPCs nearby who did. <br /> <br />Now this is where many ask what the difference is, because under both systems, you get rewards for going out and killing monsters. Indeed, aside from having to do less traveling and less talking to NPCs under FFXIV's system, one could say that the underlying mechanics are almost identical. But then the mechanics of it were never really the issue. The issue was in the <i>delivery</i> of those mechanics, in the way Levequests present their storylines to the player. <br /> <br />Yes, the way Levequests are set up does have you doing essentially the same sort of tasks that regular quests in any other MMO have you do. The difference, however, is that getting all of your quests from the same place all the time reduces the amount of variety in the game. When a quest can be obtained from absolutely anywhere, the game feels more like a real, living, breathing world. But when all the quests come from a single place, everywhere outside that place feels empty and lifeless. <br /> <br />And then when the NPC giving the quest is different from the NPC who actually needs help, it creates an odd sense of &quot;disconnect&quot; between the player and the NPC, making it difficult to empathize with the characters of the game. For example, consider this quest description for the Levequest <a href="HTTP://www.eorzeapedia.com/wiki/en/Meet_the_Flint_Stones" rel="external nofollow" title="www.eorzeapedia.com/wiki/en/Meet_the_Flint_Stones">Meet the Flint Stones</a>: <br /> <br /><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Quote:</div><div class="orig"><i>Drowning Wench proprietor Baderon Tenfingers requires flint stones for the tinder boxes he sells to the adventurers who frequent his alehouse. According to Baderon, suitable samples can be obtained from the various outcroppings located near Camp Bearded Rock.</i></div></div> <br /> <br />That, right there, is the entire quest description. Aside from that, there is no dialogue, no cutscenes, no anything. Two measly sentences is all you get, and then you're sent on your way. <br /> <br />And on top of that, Baderon is the NPC who needs help here, but never at any point during this quest do you ever have to so much as glance at Baderon. Instead, the quest is given to you by Piralnaut, a Levequest NPC who acts as sort of a middle-man in the Adventurer's Guild. It is Piralnaut who gives you the quest, and Piralnaut who you report back to when the quest is completed. Baderon isn't even involved in the process in any way, aside from being briefly mentioned in your Quest Log as the NPC who needs help. The name could have been swapped out for Fred or Bob or George and it wouldn't have changed the story or the mechanics in the slightest. <br /> <br />Now comes that WoW comparison I promised earlier. Just read the above quest description and see how stark a contrast it is to this other quest from World of Warcraft, called <a href="HTTP://www.wowwiki.com/Quest:A_Dark_Threat_Looms#Description" rel="external nofollow" title="www.wowwiki.com/Quest:A_Dark_Threat_Looms#Description">A Dark Threat Looms</a>, given to you by a dwarf named Chief Engineer Hinderweir VII: <br /> <br /><div class="msgQuote"><div class="source">Quote:</div><div class="orig"><i><b><u>Quest Description:</u></b> <br />Thank the stars someone is concerned about the well-being of the Dam. First the destruction of the Thandol Span and then the pillaging of Dun Modr! I have no doubt that the Dam will be the target of the next Dark Iron threat. Most of the security detail here was reassigned to the Alliance Front, including my top inspector. <br /> <br />That's why I need you, &lt;name&gt;. I spotted some Dark Iron Sappers milling about the eastern ramp of the Dam. Investigate the area and bring back a clue. <br /> <br /><b><u>Objectives Summary:</u></b> <br />Investigate the area near the eastern ramp of the Dam and bring Chief Engineer Hinderweir a clue that might reveal what the Dark Iron Dwarves are up to.</i></div></div> <br /> <br />Did you notice the difference in presentation there? World of Warcraft has both a quest description <b>AND</b> an objectives summary, while what FFXIV has is essentially just an objectives summary with a tiny bit more detail. Both quests have background stories to them, but WoW's quests have actual NPC dialogue behind them, while FFXIV's Levequests do not. And without full and proper NPC dialogue, the storylines for Levequests in FFXIV lack personality and flair in their presentation. The actual content itself isn't the problem, but rather the way the content is presented. <br /> <br />FFXIV's style of getting all your Levequests from the same place may be nice and convenient if you don't particularly care about story, and just want to plow through content as quickly as possible (something that a lot of WoW players actually do), but people who want a bit of flavor to the lore of their quests will feel left out in the cold. And considering this a FINAL FANTASY game we're talking about here, ignoring those diehard fans who expect a decent story isn't a good idea. <br /> <br />Of course, this is just about the Levequests in FFXIV, which are not the only kind of quest that FFXIV has. Thanks to a wealth of cinematic cutscenes, the Main Scenario Quests in FFXIV are, from what I've seen, far superior in their presentation. So much so that after my first two days of playing FFXIV I felt more engrossed in the story of the game than I've ever felt in WoW. If the Levequests all had the same quality of presentation found in the Main Scenario Quests, no one would be complaining. As it is, typical Levequests in FFXIV have about as much personality in their stories as an objectives summary from WoW (which isn't meant to have personality, anyway), and are completely lacking the more flavorful quest descriptions and NPC dialogue which make a quest feel like more than just an errand. <br /> <br />But then making cinematic cutscenes for every Levequest in the entire game would probably be asking too much. Not that I wouldn't love to see that, but Square-Enix <i>does</i> have limited resources, limited manpower, and limited time; and with the rapid development rate that is expected of MMORPGs, it's not realistically feasible to make that many cutscenes and still pump out new content at a decent rate. So then what is the solution to this problem? <br /> <br />The answer is simple: FFXIV already has a nifty little feature called the NPC Linkshell, which allows certain NPCs to contact you from absolutely anywhere in the game world for the sole purpose of feeding you story-related dialogue and giving you tips on what to do next. Why not employ this feature to help add a bit of personality and flavor to the storylines of each Levequest? Imagine it: when you begin a new Levequest, instead of simply teleporting to the designated camp right away, the NPC who needs help first contacts you via the NPC Linkshell and gives story-related dialogue to enhance your experience and help pull you into the story of the game more effectively. And since the NPC Linkshells are nothing but plain text that appears in the chatlog, NPC dialogue for them could be produced quickly and easily. This would make Levequests far more entertaining than they are now, and would greatly enhance the enjoyment we all get out of the game. <br /> <br /><i><span class="sm">Edited, Nov 12th 2010  1:06am by Rhianu </span></i></div>
